<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-708-855  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 708 855.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  May 1989 v26 n5 p36(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Resonant-mode power supplies: a primer. (more wattage in smallerpackages)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sykes, Frederick E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Resonant mode sine-wave shaping may be used in the future inmilitary avionics and in telecommunications.andP;  The technologyyields ultracompact, highly efficient supplies with high powerdensity that can be built relatively inexpensively.andP;  Incomingcurrent and voltage are stored alternately in an inductor andcapacitor that shape them into sinusoids that drive the powertransformer.andP;  Few of the topologies possible in resonant mode havebeen tried or used in production, possibly because advantages anddisadvantages of those topologies are not known.andP;  There areseveral essential things to consider in the design of componentsfor resonant-mode power supplies.andP;  The resonant tank must storeenough energy to supply maximum load under the lowest line voltageand must be balanced with the need to minimize current cyclingback and forth from the tank to the line.andP;  It may be difficult todesign a power supply for large input voltage ranges.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Power SupplyNew TechniqueMiniaturizationSwitching TheoryVoltageConverters.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   Defining terms. (table)Features of common resonant-mode topologies. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>